{"questionId":"21414","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>If a shark is spotted near to Brighton beach, a lifeguard will activate a siren to warn swimmers.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/b21c292ab6eb78c743eabd2bf2c70f1d0a84b21e.png\"></p>\n<p>The sound intensity, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math>, of the siren varies inversely with the square of the distance, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi></math>, from&nbsp;the siren, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>d</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>It is known that at a distance of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math> metres from the siren, the sound intensity is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> watts per&nbsp;square metre (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mtext>W m</mtext><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>).</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>k</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>k</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> The <em><strong>AG</strong> </em>line must be seen for the second <em><strong>M1</strong></em> to be awarded. <br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Award no marks for substituting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> into&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>&nbsp;(i.e., working backwards).</p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"21414","referenceCode":"21M.1.SL.TZ1.11a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Show that I=9d2.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Modelling functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}